			<h4><a id="comment_link_64190432" name="comment_link_64190432" href="//news.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=23206200&amp;cid=64190432" onclick="return D2.setFocusComment(64190432)" >Re:</a>


		 	<span id="comment_score_64190432" class="score"> (<a href="#" onclick="getModalPrefs('modcommentlog', 'Moderation Comment Log', 64190432); return false"><span class=opt>Score:</span>2</a>)</span></h4>
		</div>
		<div class="details">
			<span class="by"><span class="byby">by </span><a href="//slashdot.org/~Powercntrl">Powercntrl</a>  <span class="uid"><a href="//slashdot.org/~Powercntrl">( 458442 )</a></span></a></span><span class="writes" style="display:none"> writes:</span> 
			<span class="otherdetails" id="comment_otherdetails_64190432"></span>
		</div>
	</div>
	<div class="commentBody">
		<div id="comment_body_64190432"><p><div class="quote"><p>No heat during winter to save battery</p></div><p>A few ingenious folks who live in colder climates have fit diesel-fueled heaters to their EVs.  The heaters were originally designed for truckers to keep the sleeper cab area warm without having to idle the engine all night.  They operate with a very clean burn and since there's not really much efficiency loss involved in burning fuel for heat, you don't need very much of it.</p><p>Generic Chinese versions of the heaters go for about $100, so it's a pretty cheap fix.</p></div>
	</div>

	<div class="commentSub" id="comment_sub_64190432">

