	<div class="commentBody">
		<div id="comment_body_64190594"><p>1. anyone that thinks ambient temperature doesn't effect battery efficiency wasn't paying attention in high school physical sciences.<br>2. anyone that thinks they can roll into a charger at 1% and have a zero-probability of issues is a fucking idiot that probably used to wait until their fuel gauge was below the E before pulling up to a fuel pump in an ICE vehicle.<br>3. Some EVs (Tesla for sure, not certain about others) allow you to schedule a departure, which will cause the car to heat up the battery pack to retain thermal efficiency before you go, which results in partial mitigation of the issue even if you use some of your battery to heat the pack.  I used this to drive across Wyoming and Utah in single-digit temperatures in December of 2021 without any problems, driving past superchargers because I still had plenty of distance to go to the next one, with a good &gt;15% margin to spare.</p><p>TL;DR: you can't fix stupid, and RTFM.</p></div>
	</div>

